Hi Parag,

&gt; You might work around this limitation by placing all test cases and
&gt; assert statements sequentially inside a single method. This
&gt; approachsuffers from two limitations. The first limitation is the
&gt; need to replicate the test code for every test case. Even if you
&gt; have only two or three lines of code per test case, the size of the
&gt; method will mushroom and become hard to maintain (and read). See
&gt; example below

Consider extracting the repeated code into a separate method, somehing
like this:


private void checkCreate_Label(String date, String lot,              

                               String parm3, String expectedLabel)
{
    try {
        BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(date, lot, parm3);
        assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(expectedLabel)) ;
    } catch (Exception e) {
        assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
    }
}

private void checkCreate_Exception(String date, String lot,
                                   String parm3,
                                   Class expectedException)
{
    try {
        BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(date, lot, parm3);
    } catch (Exception e) {
        assert(&quot;Wrong Exception thrown: &quot; + e,
               e.getClass().equals(expectedException)) ;
    }
}

public void testCreateBatchLabelNoInnerClass()
{
    checkCreate_Label(&quot;20010530&quot;, &quot;A13&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, &quot;A13-1 EXP. 05/01&quot;);
    checkCreate_Label(&quot;20010530&quot;, &quot;A13&quot;, &quot;&quot;, &quot;A13 EXP. 05/01&quot;);
    checkCreate_Label(&quot;20011231&quot;, &quot;A13&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, &quot;A13-1 EXP. 12/01&quot;);
    checkCreate_Label(&quot;20010101&quot;, &quot;A13&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, &quot;A13-1 EXP. 01/01&quot;);
    checkCreate_Label(&quot;20010101&quot;, &quot;A123&quot;, &quot;99&quot;, &quot;A123-99 EXP. 01/01&quot;);

    checkCreate_Exception(&quot;2001530&quot;, &quot;A999&quot;, &quot;&quot;, BadDateException.class);
    checkCreate_Exception(&quot;20010530&quot;, &quot;913&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, BadLotException.class);

// etc

}

I&#39;ve just done that for a bunch of my own tests.  The one drawback is
that I have to scan more the stack trace to identify the actual test,
but so far I haven&#39;t found that to be a problem.

